{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639240"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:04:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:04:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17768"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17768"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.08,0.04,0.17,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10482"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72276"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10482","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10482"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17768"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57746"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7195"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24464"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24467"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72276"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following reflexes may be tested to evaluate cranial nerve five?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Jaw jerk reflex and corneal reflex","Gag reflex and pupillary light reflex","Corneal reflex and pupillary light reflex","Jaw jerk reflex and gag reflex","Pupillary light reflex and accommodation reflex"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ejaw jerk reflex\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorneal reflex\u003C/strong\u003E are both used to evaluate the function of cranial nerve five, also known as the trigeminal nerve. The jaw jerk reflex is a monosynaptic reflex that tests the motor component of the trigeminal nerve, specifically the mandibular branch, which innervates the muscles of mastication. A brisk jaw jerk reflex may indicate an upper motor neuron lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorneal reflex\u003C/strong\u003E tests the sensory component of the trigeminal nerve, specifically the ophthalmic branch, which provides sensation to the cornea. The reflex involves blinking in response to corneal stimulation, with the efferent limb mediated by the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egag reflex\u003C/strong\u003E is used to assess cranial nerves nine and ten, while the \u003Cstrong\u003Epupillary light reflex\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eaccommodation reflex\u003C/strong\u003E are used to assess cranial nerve three. These reflexes are not related to the trigeminal nerve.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve V) is responsible for sensory innervation of the face and motor functions such as mastication.","The jaw jerk reflex and corneal reflex are used to assess the function of the trigeminal nerve.","The jaw jerk reflex tests the motor component of the trigeminal nerve, while the corneal reflex tests the sensory component."],"references":["Khan ZA. Revisiting the Corneal and Blink Reflexes for Primary and Secondary Trigeminal Facial Pain Differentiation. Pain Res Manag. 2021 Feb 9;2021:6664736. doi: 10.1155/2021/6664736. PMID: 33628353; PMCID: PMC7886525.","Ogino MH, Tadi P. Neuroanatomy, Trigeminal Reflexes. [Updated 2023 Jun 5]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551641/","Peterson DC, Hamel RN. Corneal Reflex. 2023 Jul 25. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30480980."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57746"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17768"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57746"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T06:21:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T06:22:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10482"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72276"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"p